Binary Operators with Booleans¶

https://www.udemy.com/course/the-ultimate-pandas-bootcamp-advanced-python-data-analysis/learn/lecture/18839288#overview

Binary : OR operator " | "

In [32]:
True | False   #True OR False
Out[32]:
True
In [33]:
False | False
Out[33]:
False
In [34]:
False | True
Out[34]:
True
In [35]:
True | True
Out[35]:
True
  • think of the "OR" operator as searching for True

Binary : AND operator " & "¶

In [36]:
True & False
Out[36]:
False
In [37]:
False & True
Out[37]:
False
In [38]:
False & False
Out[38]:
False
In [39]:
True & True
Out[39]:
True

The way to think about the "AND" operator is - Always True unless there is a FALSE

  • A single False is enough to trigger a False
In [41]:
True & True &  True &  False &  True
Out[41]:
False
In [42]:
#creating a single element series with a Single False value
f = pd.Series(False)
In [43]:
f
Out[43]:
0    False
dtype: bool
In [44]:
t = pd.Series(True)
In [45]:
t
Out[45]:
0    True
dtype: bool
In [46]:
#Lets combine them using a Binary operator
t & f
Out[46]:
0    False
dtype: bool
In [47]:
t | f
Out[47]:
0    True
dtype: bool
In [49]:
#Lets convert these Series to longer ranges of Booleans
#For every even position item , it should be True otherwise False
t = pd.Series([True if i%2 == 0 else False for i in range(10)])

Important thing to note here is : when we combine two Pandas Series the comparison is done Label to Label not based on the order

In [66]:
#Lets create a Series with Index Labels
f = pd.Series(data= [ False , True , True] , index = ['c' , 'b' , 'a'])
In [62]:
f
Out[62]:
c    False
b     True
a     True
dtype: object
In [67]:
t = pd.Series(data = [True , False , False] , index = ['a' , 'b' , 'c'])
In [64]:
t
Out[64]:
a     True
b    False
c    False
dtype: object

So, when we say "f & t" we are technically expecting three False:

In [68]:
#But we end up getting two False
f & t
Out[68]:
a     True
b    False
c    False
dtype: bool
In [69]:
t & f
Out[69]:
a     True
b    False
c    False
dtype: bool
  • The order of the elements is not important here , what is important is the LABEL that these boolean values are associated with.
  • (t) Label a : (f) Label a
  • (t) Label b : (f) Label b
  • (t) Label c : (f) Label c

So, remember , whenever combining Series the comparison happens by Label , not based on the order

XOR and Complement Binary Ops¶

Binary XOR stands for Exclusive OR : How is it different from the regular OR ?

  • Its True only when the inputs are different and False when they are alike or similar
  • The XOR Binary operator is represented using the ^ (Carat) symbol
In [70]:
#This is True because inputs are different
True ^ False
Out[70]:
True
In [71]:
True ^ True
Out[71]:
False
In [72]:
False ^ True
Out[72]:
True
In [73]:
False ^ False
Out[73]:
False

Binary Two's Operator , represented using "~" Tilde¶

In pandas and Numpy , you will find it extremely useful when negating the Boolean Mask.

  • In other words finding the Opposite of Boolean Series
In [74]:
~True
Out[74]:
-2
In [75]:
~False
Out[75]:
-1

This has to do with how computers represent integers

To do DataFrame Selection along the Index Axis , the length of our Boolean Series needs to be the same as the length of the Index iteself.

There is an alternative way of indexing along the columns , that is to, Chain two square brackets¶

[ ] Chaining¶

In [136]:
#Chelsea players and 23 years old or younger
chelsea_23under = (players.club == 'Chelsea') & (players.age <= 23)
In [137]:
players[chelsea_23under]

  • Now we can extend the square brackets
  • Right next to it we can chain on a second Square bracket and say , give me just 'position'

Fancy Indexing with Lookup¶

In [142]:
#players.loc[0 : 2] => Slicing
#players.loc[players.age > 37] => boolean masking
#players.loc[132 , 'name']  => basic(label-based) Indexing
#players.loc[[0,132],['name' , 'market_value']] => Fancy Indexing

Fancy Indexing Item Selection : lookup() is another way to fancy Indexing¶

The method is called "lookup()"

  • It take a specific "Row label" and a specific "Column Label" , then it returns the value associated with each pair of labels
In [143]:
#We have here traditional label based selection using the .loc indexer with some fancy indexing 
#We are passing a list of index labels as well as a Tuple of column labels
players.loc[[0, 132] , ('name' , 'market_value')] #fancy
Out[143]:
name market_value
0 Alexis Sanchez 65.0
132 Connor Wickham 6.0
In [147]:
players.iloc[[0, 132] , [0 , 5]]
Out[147]:
name market_value
0 Alexis Sanchez 65.0
132 Connor Wickham 6.0
In [148]:
#Lets compare this with the Lookup method
In [149]:
players.lookup([0 , 132] , ['name' , 'market_value'])
Out[149]:
array(['Alexis Sanchez', 6.0], dtype=object)

Another Example :¶

The lookup() function returns label-based "fancy indexing" function for DataFrame. Given equal-length arrays of row and column labels, return an array of the values corresponding to each (row, col) pair.

In [157]:
players.set_index('name').head(3)
Out[157]:
club age position position_cat market_value page_views fpl_value fpl_sel fpl_points region nationality new_foreign age_cat club_id big_club new_signing
name
Alexis Sanchez Arsenal 28 LW 1 65.0 4329 12.0 17.10% 264 3 Chile 0 4 1 1 0
Mesut Ozil Arsenal 28 AM 1 50.0 4395 9.5 5.60% 167 2 Germany 0 4 1 1 0
Petr Cech Arsenal 35 GK 4 7.0 1529 5.5 5.90% 134 2 Czech Republic 0 6 1 1 0
In [155]:
#List of Index Labels
names = ['Petr Cech' , 'Mesut Ozil' , 'Alexis Sanchez']
In [156]:
#List of Column Labels
attributes = ['age' , 'market_value' , 'page_views']
In [152]:
#Lets say we are interested in getting : 
#'Petr Cech' ==> 'age'
#'Mesut Ozil' ==> 'market_value'
#'Alexis Sanchez' ==> 'page_views'

In [154]:
#We can set the index on the fly instead of doing it in place
players.set_index('name').lookup(names , attributes)
Out[154]:
array([  35.,   50., 4329.])

lookup() gives us the flexibility to select precise values in a DataFrame using a collection of Row and column labels.

  • Kind of like hunting down values using their Label coordinates.

Sorting VS Reordering¶

What if we want to Re-order our Dataframe according to a very specific order that our Boss specifies

  • We could use the reindex() method
In [191]:

#I will use the location based indexer
#I will select first four rows and columns
players.iloc[:4 , :4]

1 Aaron Lennon Everton 30 RW

players_lite = players.iloc[:4 , :4]

players_lite
Out[193]:
name club age position

Lets say we want to specifically order the Rows here , acc to a highly specific requirement

In [194]:
#lets say the row order needs to be 2 ,1 ,3 , 0

Identifying Dupes¶

Data needs a lot of handling , manipulation , organization and cleaning

Our players dataframe here contains some duplicate records.

  • Duplicate records are the ones which have same values across all columns
  • These records will cause a lot of problems , lets say we want to figure out the avg age of each player or the market_value etc. If you have the same player showing multiple times , that resulting calculation will be incorrect or biased because that player is overrepresented in the sample.

What really constitutes a Duplicated value?¶

The values across each column need to be the same for two records to be considered duplicate.

In [246]:
players[players['name'].str.endswith('Oxlade-Chamberlain')]
Out[246]:

19 Alex Oxlade-Chamberlain Arsenal 23 RM 2 22.0 1519 6.0 1.80% 83 1 England 0 2 1 1 0

What if "Arsenal" shows up 15 times with slightly different "page_views" . Those will be considered unique records.

  • But for most use cases out there , we would not want to treat them as unique. Lets say we are calculating the total markey value of Arsenal players , we don't want Alex to show up 15 times.
  • So we should somehow have a way to define precisely what constitutes a unique value.
  • In Python we can define a subset of columns that should be considered
In [247]:
#the subset parameter
  • Lets say we want the Uniques to be characterised by 'club' , 'age' , 'position' , 'market_value'

All the records that repeat only these four fields should be considered Duplicates

Now we got 7 rows

This is great but it brings up another question. Which one is the Duplicate?

By default - the first occurance of the record is the original

keep = 'last'¶

In a set of Duplicate records , the 'last' occurance will be considered the original value and everything preceding it will be marked as a Duplicate. But at the end of the day , the number of Duplicates will remain the same.

In [251]:
players.loc[players.duplicated(subset = ['club' , 'age', 'position' , 'market_value'] , keep = 'last')].shape
Out[251]:
(7, 17)

keep = 'first'¶

In a set of Duplicate records , the 'first' occurance will be considered the original value and everything following it will be marked as Duplicates .

In [252]:
players.loc[players.duplicated(subset = ['club' , 'age', 'position' , 'market_value'] , keep = 'first')].shape
Out[252]:
(7, 17)

keep = False¶

We want all the repeating values to be treated as Duplicates (meaning dont keep any matching records)

In [253]:
players.loc[players.duplicated(subset = ['club' , 'age', 'position' , 'market_value'] , keep = False)].shape
Out[253]:
(13, 17)

Syntax : "players.pop("age")"

3 Points to consider¶

  • pop() returns the removed ('popped') column as a Series
  • pop() modifies the underlying dataframe (operates inplace)

The default axis for this method is 0

  • We copy forward from the previous row record , it is the preceding Row label.
  • When we change to axis = 1 , it happens horizontally , which does not make much sense
  • because the value is copied from the previous column
  • But its good to know that this kind of fill value behaviour is possible

Similar to 'ffill' we have a 'bfill' method which stands for "backward fill"

fill directions¶

  • Method ffill => axis =1 - Left to Right
  • Method ffill => axis =0 Top to Bottom
  • Method bfill => axis =0 Bottom to Top
  • Method bfill => axis =1 Right to Left

This is mostly useful in TimeSeries datasets

#ffill => 'pad'
#bfill => 'backfill'

Define the random transformation function¶

  • Defining a function:
    • Apply a random string capitalization method
    • Apply to a sequence of values and
    • It should return the transformed sequence
  • we define a function called random_case
  • In the end , this function will be called from within transform()
  • It should only focus on string columns
In [438]:
#here x will always represent a column
#choice will select a string function randomly to be applied to the column 
#we add the parenthesis to actually invoke the function
#choice(funcs)()

def random_case(x):
    funcs = [x.str.swapcase, x.str.lower, x.str.title , x.str.upper]
    
    return choice(funcs)()

The Dataframe apply() method gives us the opportunity to apply a function across the entire DataFrame , one row or one column at a time.

  • We want to modify all our floating point columns and round them to the closest integer without actually converting them to integer
  • we start by defining a function called round_floats()
  • to check if the dtype is float , return the rounded version of that series , if not we return the Series unchanged
  • Remember x will be a series when this function runs and series will have the dtype attribute.
  • Thats why we are checking the dtype first.
In [447]:
def round_floats(x):
    if x.dtype == np.float64:
        return round(x)
    
    return x

  • Lets assume , in addition to making the adjustment for inflation , we also want to know precisely , when each one hundered'th value was adjusted for Inflation.

In [474]:
#We first set the counter , so we know when each one -hunderedth value is adjusted
#define the function
#set the counter as global
#incremenet the counter by 1
#if counter is a multiple of 100 in other words, the remainder when divided by 100 is 0
#we want to printout a notification
#We are conditionally printing the notification but for all values we are adjusting the Inflation as well
#One quick note : The Syntax that we are using for string is called : "Literal String Interpolation"
#or f strings

from datetime import datetime
counter = 0

def log_and_transform(x):
    global counter
    counter += 1
    if counter % 100 == 0:
        print(f"It's {datetime.now()} and I adjusted the {counter}th  value.")
        
    return x * inflation

Skill Challenege¶

Create a Standalone function that :¶

- accepts a single parameter x
- returns the string 'relatively unknown' if x is less than 220
- 'kind of popular' if x is between 220 and 600(non-inclusive)
- 'popular' if x is between 600 and 2000 (non-inclusive)
- 'super-popular' otherwise
In [508]:
def get_popularity(x):
    if x < 220:
        return 'relatively unknown'
    elif x < 600:
        return 'kind of popular'
    elif x < 2000:
        return 'popular'
    else:
        return 'Super Popular'

<ipython-input-538-ed0c557f33c5>:3: SettingWithCopyWarning: 
A value is trying to be set on a copy of a slice from a DataFrame

See the caveats in the documentation: https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/indexing.html#returning-a-view-versus-a-copy
  players['page_views'][2] = 2001

Warning : A value is trying to be set on a copy of a slice from a DataFrame¶

Reason : Because Pandas cannot guarantee that we are working with the actual underlying DataFrame , when we do indexing like this , which is called "chain indexing" , and specifically we are doing assignment using chain indexing.

If we are working with the copy of the DataFrame , any change that we do to that copy does not change the underlying data. So pandas cannot guarantee that the assignment that we are trying to do will be reflected in the underlying DataFrame.

One solution is to reassign the copy of this Dataframe to the dataframe itself and try the code again:¶

View VS Copy¶

A VIEW is like a window into the undelying Data. Its like an opening that gives us direct access to the data. If we modify what we see , we are modifying the df.

A COPY on the other hand is a replica of whats in the dataframe. So if we change the copy we dont affect the underlying df.

But how do we know if we are working with a copy or a window.

2 Point Rule:¶

Pandas loves to give us copies.

BUT

if we use loc / iloc or at / iat , we are guaranteed to get a view

When the inplace parameter is set to False then we are guaranteed to get copies of the dataframe. So , in those instances we are just changing the copy and it will not impact the underlying data.

  • Lets say , we need to change a couple of values and we need to be guaranteed that we are working with a view. We want to make sure that the values in the underlying Dataframe change and we also want to avoid the setting with copy warning.

  • its advisable to use 'loc' / 'iloc' or 'at' / 'iat' indexers
